Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Caehowel, Kinnerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","of Caehowel,Kinnerley,Shropshire,England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sutton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called Sutton, named with Old English <i>sūth</i> ‘south, southern’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The English surname is also common in Ireland (Wexford, Kildare), where it has been established since the 13th century and Gaelicized as <b>de Sutún</b>.","Jewish (from the former Ottoman Empire, including Syria): unexplained.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>(bi) suthentune</i> ‘(at the place to the) south of the village’."],"variants":[{"name":"Setton","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avi, Ronit, Yossef.  French Andree, Henri, Jacques, Maryse.","Jewish (from the Ottoman Empire): altered form of   Sutton  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Seaton  ."]}]},{"name":"Gruffudd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."],"variants":[{"name":"Griffudd","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Gruffud","meanings":["From Old Welsh <i>Grip(p)iud</i>, from an unexplained first element + a second element meaning ‘lord, prince’.  Gruffydd ap Llewelyn  (  d. 1063 ) was one of the most able rulers of Wales in the Middle Ages, scoring notable victories over the English until he was eventually defeated by  King Harold  in  1063 ."]},{"name":"Griffith","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Gruffudd ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Gruffudd de Sutton ap Gervase Coch was born in 1150, in Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Iorwerth Goch ap Maredudd, was 41 and his mother, Maud de Manley, was 61. He married Matilda verch Ieuan about 1189, in Kinnerley, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1221, in Wales, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1150–1221":"1150–1221","1154–Female":"1154–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1190–1280":"1190–1280","1110–1171":"1110–1171","1090–Female":"1090–Surnud","1190":"1190","1090":"1090","about 1171":"umbes 1171","about 1190":"umbes 1190","ABT 1189":"umbes 1189","1221":"1221","1110":"1110","1154":"1154","1150":"1150","1171":"1171","1160":"1160","1280":"1280","Cae Howel, Kinnerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Caehowel, Kinnerley, Shropshire, England":"Kinnerley, Sh